05362nam a22007575i 9780813570716DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2014035922  a97808135707167 a10.36019/97808135707162doi  a(DE-B1597)530302  a(OCoLC)920231442  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPS153.A84bH585 2015 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a810.9/8952231 aHo, Jennifer Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRacial Ambiguity in Asian American Culture /cJennifer Ann Ho. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsian American Studies Today00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Ambiguous Americans -- t1. From Enemy Alien to Assimilating American: Yoshiko deLeon and the Mixed-Marriage Policy of the Japanese American Incarceration -- t2. Antisentimental Loss: Stories of Transracial/Transnational Asian American Adult Adoptees in the Blogosphere -- t3. Cablinasian Dreams, Amerasian Realities: Transcending Race in the Twenty-First Century and Other Myths Broken by Tiger Woods -- t4. Ambiguous Movements and Mobile Subjectivity: Passing in between Autobiography and Fiction with Paisley Rekdal and Ruth Ozeki -- t5. Transgressive Texts and Ambiguous Authors: Racial Ambiguity in Asian American Literature -- tCoda: Ending with Origins: My Own Racial Ambiguity -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe sheer diversity of the Asian American populace makes them an ambiguous racial category. Indeed, the 2010 U.S. Census lists twenty-four Asian-ethnic groups, lumping together under one heading people with dramatically different historical backgrounds and cultures. In Racial Ambiguity in Asian American Culture, Jennifer Ann Ho shines a light on the hybrid and indeterminate aspects of race, revealing ambiguity to be paramount to a more nuanced understanding both of race and of what it means to be Asian American. Exploring a variety of subjects and cultural artifacts, Ho reveals how Asian American subjects evince a deep racial ambiguity that unmoors the concept of race from any fixed or finite understanding. For example, the book examines the racial ambiguity of Japanese American nisei Yoshiko Nakamura deLeon, who during World War II underwent an abrupt transition from being an enemy alien to an assimilating American, via the Mixed Marriage Policy of 1942. It looks at the blogs of Korean, Taiwanese, and Vietnamese Americans who were adopted as children by white American families and have conflicted feelings about their “honorary white” status. And it discusses Tiger Woods, the most famous mixed-race Asian American, whose description of himself as “Cablinasian”—reflecting his background as Black, Asian, Caucasian, and Native American—perfectly captures the ambiguity of racial classifications. Race is an abstraction that we treat as concrete, a construct that reflects only our desires, fears, and anxieties. Jennifer Ho demonstrates in Racial Ambiguity in Asian American Culture that seeing race as ambiguous puts us one step closer to a potential antidote to racism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexAsian American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAsian Americans in popular culture. 0aAsian AmericansxRace identity. 0aRacially mixed peoplexRace identityzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete e